				 Sop hope for textile exporters
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Nov. 15: The government is likely to offer service tax sops to textile exporters and lower interest rates, to help them cover their losses.																								Some representatives of the textile-export sector met finance minister P. Chidambaram today, to discuss their problems. The sector has been affected by the rising rupee. Officials of the State Bank of India, Canara Bank and the Bank of India were also present.The finance minister will examine all suggestions and definitely take some measures, M.B.N. Rao, chairman of Canara Bank, told reporters after the meeting. 																								On the options available before the government, Rao said, Financial measures are one aspect but a more comprehensive approach is needed. I am sure the finance ministry is aware of the situation and the government will take all possible measures for textiles.																								We want a 2 per cent interest rate subvention for export credit. Export credit should be provided at 6 per cent, which is equivalent to the bank rate, said M.S. Mathivanan, chairman of the Powerloom Development and Export Promotion Council. The average export credit interest rate is 8.5 per cent, trade analysts said.																								Textile exporters also took up issues relating to the reimbursement of service tax and state levies at the meeting. Apart from the rupees appreciation, these taxes are also responsible for our losses, added Mathivanan.																								Bank of Baroda move																								State-run Bank of Baroda (BoB) will raise Rs 2,000 crore in the last quarter of this fiscal to meet Basel II norms and credit requirement.																								The Mumbai-based bank today increased interest rates on term deposits by 25 to 50 basis points on various maturities effective from today. We plan to raise around Rs 2,000 crore through tier II bonds by February next year, said A.K. Khandelwal, chairman and MD of BoB. 
